DESC: 1. Action Code: Award2. Date:Â August 29Â 20173. Year: Fiscal Year 20174. Contracting Office Zip Code: 222045. Classification Code: U6. Contracting Office Address: 701 S. Courthouse Rd, Arlington, VA 222047. Subject: Marine Maker Initiative Support8. Proposed Solicitation Number: M95494-17-T-00329. Closing Response Date: 6 July 201710. Contact Point or Contracting Officer: Jessica Harker; jessica.harker@usmc.mil 11. Contract Award and Solicitation Number: M95494-17-T-0032 / M95494-17-C-003212. Contract Award Dollar Amount: $3,955,263.3113. Contract Line Item Number: CLINs 0001-000614. Contract Award Date: 25 August 201715. Contractor: Building Momentum, LLC16. Description: Headquarters Marine Corps (HQMC), Deputy Commandant, Installations and Logistics (DC IL) Expeditionary Logistics Division requires support for the training, equipment, online resource development and community facilitation support for the Marine Maker Initiative. This initiative began in 2016, as part of the 2015 Secretary of the Navy (SECNAV) Implementation Plan for Additive Manufacturing. This particular initiative focuses on workforce development of digital design and manufacturing technologies. This contract provides support to the Marine Maker Initiative, and is intended to enable Marines with the training and tools necessary to better develop tactical solutions to problems. This initiative includes four different types of training in various locations both CONUS and OCONUS, online training and resource development, refinement of the digital collaboration website, and purchasing of equipment to include 3D Manufacturing Kits, Fabrication Kits, Robotics Kits, and Electronics Kits. The performance period for this contractÂ has a one-year base period with two (2) one-year option periods.r17. Place of Contract Performance: Performance will be at the Contractors Facilities. Travel is required to support the training events held at DoD Facilities both CONUS / OCONUS. 18. Set-Aside Status: This is a sole-source direct award to a Service Disabled Veteran Owned Small Business (SDVOSB) IAW FAR 19.1406 and FAR 6.302-5(b)(6).19. Rationale for Small Business strategy: After reviewing the results of a Market Survey, MCICOM identified one SDVOSB capable of fulfilling the requirement in its entirety. FAR 19.203(c) states that the contracting officer shall first consider an acquisition for the small business socioeconomic contracting programs before considering a small business set-aside. This is further echoed in FAR 19.1406 (a), which states that a contracting officer shall consider a contract award to an SDVOSB concern on a sole source basis before considering small business set-asides.While there are other small businesses that may be interested in fulfilling this requirement, in accordance with FAR 19.203 (Relationship Among Small Business Programs), there is no order of preference among the various socioeconomic contracting programs. The Government should consider the market research and agency progress in fulfilling small business goals in making its decision on which program to utilize. The Government has taken both of those aspects into consideration in its decision to utilize the authority prescribed at FAR 19.1406 to contract directly with an SDVOSB for this requirement. The Small Business Specialist concurred with this determination on 22 June 2017.

DESC: August 29, 2017Re: Lease No. GS-07P-LTX00297, FEMA, Austin, TXIn response to a request for approximately 200,000 ANSI/BOMA Office Area (ABOA) square feet of officeand related space in Austin, TX for immediate occupancy, we have accepted the offer of B.H. 11000NORTH IH 35, LLC to provide 122,075 ABOA square feet of space at 11000 North IH 35 in Austin, TX. Thecontract price was $3,051,875.00 for a term of 12 months with 6 months firm.8/25/17rFEMAAustin, TXHurricane Harvey Response Contracting Officer CertificationAttachment 2GENERAL SERVICES ADMINISTRATION CLASS JUSTIFICATION FOR OTHER THAN FULL AND OPEN COMPETITIONrACQUISITIONS OF SPACE AND RELATED SERVICES TO SUPPORT FEDERAL AGENCIES ACTING IN RESPONSE TO EMERGENCIES OR MAJOR DISASTER SITUATIONS AS HEREIN SPECIFIEDrIdentification and description of action being approved.rThis class justification for other than full and open competition is for use by the General Services Administrations (GSAs) contracting activities in the acquisition of space and related services for the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) and other Federal agencies responding to emergency situations and major disasters as specified below. This class justification is applicable to the following emergencies :ra. National emergencies declared by the President under applicable provisions of law, including, but not limited to, the Robert T. Stafford Disaster Relief and Emergency Assistance Act of 1988 (P. L. 100-707);rb. Emergencies declared by responding Federal agencies pursuant to statutorily authorized emergency plans or other applicable provisions of law; andrc. Emergencies of a health/safety or other (HSO) nature which so adversely impact the mission of an agency in a Government-owned or leased building as to necessitate the agencys expeditious relocation therefrom.Description of supplies or services required.rGSA Order ADM P 2400 .16A dated January 8, 1992, entitled Domestic Emergency Assistance Program, establishes GSAs overall guidance for providing assistance to Federal agencies in emergencies. The Order states that GSA must ensure that the requesting agency is provided space that meets its needs, and other services currently provided to the Federal establishment. Identification of statutory authority.rSection 303(c)(2) of the Federal Property and Administrative Services Act of 1949, as amended (41 U.S.C. 253(c)(2)), provides for contracting without full and open competition when there is an unusual and compelling urgency.rDemonstration that the acquisition requires use of the authority cite .rPursuant to the authority and responsibilities contained in the Federal Property and Administrative Services Act of 1949, as amended, GSA is often called upon to provide work space and related support services to Federal agencies in emergency situations. The need to provide such work space and services in support of disaster relief efforts is of unusual and compelling urgency, and any delay will seriously harm a critical Government program and the recipients of Federal assistance. This class justification is applicable only to individual acquisitions of work space and related supporting services provided to Federal agencies in response to the emergency or major disastersituations specified in the first paragraph of this Justification for Other Than Full and Open Competition.Description of efforts to obtain as many offers as practicable.rA market survey shall be conducted and competition shall be solicited to the maximum extent possible from as many potential sources as is practicable, consistent with the circumstances of the particular emergency.Determination that the anticipated cost will be fair and reasonable.rThe Government anticipates being able to negotiate a fair and reasonable price, taking into account market conditions existing at the time of acquisition.Description of the market survey conducted.rIt is impossible to identify sources capable of providing space for emergency or disaster relief in advance of the determination of individual need.As the need for space arises, a market survey will be conducted.All potential sources which can be located within the timeframe, and which can provide habitable space suitable for the needs of the responding agency, will be solicited.Other facts supporting the use of other than full and open competition.rNone.List of sources that expressed an interest in the acquisition. Not applicable.rStatement of actions to overcome barriers to competition.rUnder the circumstances described herein, there are no actions that the agency can take to overcome the barriers to full and open competition.rContracting officer certification.rThis class justification may be used by GSA contracting activities only when, with respect to each proposed lease contracting action taken pursuant to this class justification, the contracting officer executes and includes in the appropriate lease contract file the following certification:rI certify that, to the best .of my knowledge and belief, the requirement for space falls within the scope and applicability of the class justification for other than full and open competition for the acquisition of work space and related supporting services in response to emergencies ormajor disaster situations specified in the first paragraph of the class justification for other than full and open competition, entitled Identification and Description ofAction Being Approved. The Contracting Officer anticipates being able to negotiate a fair and reasonable price consistent with market conditions and the Government s requirements. rThis class justification for other than full and open competition is hereby made and approved in accordance with Section 303(c )(2) of the Federal Property and Administrative Services Act of 1949, as amended U.S.C. 253(c)(2)).Service CONCURRENCE:rArthur E. RonkovichrÂ
